Three Ol Kalou chiefs have warned those engaging in lawlessness during campaigns that they will be punished.Elijah Ng&rsquo;ang&rsquo;a of Tumaini location, his Kanjuiri counterpart Joseph Kabiru and Kagunda assistant chief Gichu Bundi said the law is not suspended because it is campaign time.The three addressed residents at Tumaini Primary School playground during a meeting convened by Nyandarua woman representative Wanjiku Muhiaon Thursday.Muhia donated makiga brick-making machine, public address systems and generators. She also donated sheep, all funded by the national government affirmative action fund programme.Ng&rsquo;ang&rsquo;a urged residents to respect politicians and allow them to share their agenda and uphold peace.He urged them to stop destroying campaign materials, whether they support the candidate or not. &ldquo;Everyone has spent money to produce these posters and other materials. Why destroy them? Ng&rsquo;ang&rsquo;a said. He urged the bodaboda operators not to be used by politicians to cause chaos.